 .SH "SUMMARY"
  
 .PP
-htpasswd is used to create and update the flat-files used to store usernames and password for basic authentication of HTTP users\&. If htpasswd cannot access a file, such as not being able to write to the output file or not being able to read the file in order to update it, it returns an error status and makes no changes\&.
+htpasswd2 is used to create and update the flat-files used to store usernames and password for basic authentication of HTTP users\&. If htpasswd2 cannot access a file, such as not being able to write to the output file or not being able to read the file in order to update it, it returns an error status and makes no changes\&.
  
 .PP
-Resources available from the Apache HTTP server can be restricted to just the users listed in the files created by htpasswd\&. This program can only manage usernames and passwords stored in a flat-file\&. It can hash and display password information for use in other types of data stores, though\&. To use a DBM database see dbmmanage or htdbm\&.
+Resources available from the Apache HTTP server can be restricted to just the users listed in the files created by htpasswd2\&. This program can only manage usernames and passwords stored in a flat-file\&. It can hash and display password information for use in other types of data stores, though\&. To use a DBM database see dbmmanage or htdbm\&.
  
 .PP
-htpasswd hashes passwords using either bcrypt, a version of MD5 modified for Apache, SHA-1, or the system's \fBcrypt()\fR routine\&. SHA-2-based hashes (SHA-256 and SHA-512) are supported for \fBcrypt()\fR\&. Files managed by htpasswd may contain a mixture of different encoding types of passwords; some user records may have bcrypt or MD5-hashed passwords while others in the same file may have passwords hashed with \fBcrypt()\fR\&.
+htpasswd2 hashes passwords using either bcrypt, a version of MD5 modified for Apache, SHA-1, or the system's \fBcrypt()\fR routine\&. SHA-2-based hashes (SHA-256 and SHA-512) are supported for \fBcrypt()\fR\&. Files managed by htpasswd2 may contain a mixture of different encoding types of passwords; some user records may have bcrypt or MD5-hashed passwords while others in the same file may have passwords hashed with \fBcrypt()\fR\&.
  
 .PP
 This manual page only lists the command line arguments\&. For details of the directives necessary to configure user authentication in httpd see the Apache manual, which is part of the Apache distribution or can be found at http://httpd\&.apache\&.org/\&.
